You may have heard about the new 💉mandate for employers in the USA over 100.

Who is enforcing it? Are they allowed to shut you down?

What options do you have if you don’t want to make you employees receive a medical procedure against their will?

I answer those questions in this video…please tag and share this with employees and business owners who don’t feel the mandate is appropriate.

Watch the video and if you’re going to take action on ANY of it, be sure to consult with a professional to help you.

This is to merely help you start the conversation.

NOTE: This is not a discussion on whether the 💉 is effective or not, it’s a post about the rights of business owners’ and their employees!

node.text:
Let’s clear up a big public accounting myth today, shall we? That myth: Coming out of college, it’s BIG 4 or BUST to have a good start to a career in public accounting.

While there is certainly a benefit to getting one of those big names on your resume, there is plenty of excellent experience to be had at regional or even smaller firms.

The key difference in experience between the Big 4 and the smaller firms is depth vs. breadth of experience.

I’ve personally never worked at a Big 4, but from the people I know who have, you get to go super deep on a specific area of the tax code—and get really good at that specific area. This can be valuable because there are “riches in the niches.”

When you work at a smaller firm, though, you get to see the entire process, from cleaning up a business owner’s messy set of books, then entering it into the business return and finally how it reflects actual tax dollars on their bottom line.

The reality is there is no better or worse, it just depends on what YOU want out of your career. But I’ve spoken with too many college kids who fear that if they don’t get a job at a Big 4 right out of the gate, that their career is over before it begins.

And that is simply not true.

Tag a friend who works in accounting! And let me know if you’d like to hear more career advice like this from me. :)

node.title: Big 4 or Bust when starting your career?

Have you relocated your business or moved into a new place recently?

Make sure you do not miss out on any potential moving deductions!

While moving expenses to relocate as an employee are no longer deductible, relocating your business is.

This means the cost to move (or buy new) furniture, the movers you hire, and the transportation expenses to get there are all definitely a tax deduction.

So be sure to pick all those in your books and don’t miss out on that expense!

Tag a business who is moving below! 🚚

node.text:
Have you considered a price increase recently? If you are growing but have not raised prices in forever, it might be time to assess your own belief in your worth!

A price increase (even a small one) is one of the easiest ways to immediately increase profits.

Consider this: if you have 20% margins—meaning for every 10 dollars of revenue you keep 2 dollars of profit—then just a 4% price increase would have the SAME impact as increase revenue volume by 20%

Yet almost no one revisits their pricing as part of their annual planning.

What I have noticed is that this is often a direct reflection of the mindset and self-worth of the owner.

So first off: consider a price increase if your business is growing.

And second: if you are feeling internal resistance to that price increase, take a look at why.

You might need to reflect on increasing your own self worth.

When is the last time you raised prices? Let me know in the comments!

node.title: Pricing is a reflection of your self-worth

With the events of the year, it seems there is a great migration going on.

Check out this video for what you need to do to make sure, if you are moving to a lower income tax state, that you avoid the high taxes of the state you leave behind!

(Hint: you ACTUALLY have to move there, and have plans to stay there permanently)

Tag someone who is moving states!

node.title: Relocating to a lower income tax state

That being said, you CAN deduct prepaid expenses up to a year in advance. Watch the video for more info!

This weekend I shared a rant based on some DMs I got when I shared with employers that if their employees want to stay on unemployment after a PPP loan funds, that the employer can stop unemployment payments.

I was overwhelmed by the positive response from business owners in my DMs, and so I wanted to share that entire story here on IGTV.

I hope it offers you some perspective, and that you will share it with employers and employees alike!

node.text:
This 9/11 anniversary is a special one because it marks 20 years since that horrible day in our country’s history.

It’s also during a period where  there seems to be more division than ever before.

We the people need to remember: we are not each others’ enemy.

We proved that 20 years ago when we came together after this gruesome attack on our soil.

It’s time to prove it again, before the USA as we know it (and take for granted) will no longer exist.

Today, I am pausing to remember those whose lives were lost on that tragic day, as well as the men and women who have fought for our freedoms in the hotbed of terror for the last 20 years.

We appreciate and honor you.

And also saying a prayer for those Americans who are currently stranded where the Taliban has taken over. 

May we not forget them, no matter what the media tries to distract our attention with.

I hope they will be brought home soon.

20 years since, and 200 years more, we will never forget.

#neverforget911 #911memorial

You may have heard about the new 💉mandate for employers in the USA over 100.

Who is enforcing it? Are they allowed to shut you down?

What options do you have if you don’t want to make you employees receive a medical procedure against their will?

I answer those questions in this video…please tag and share this with employees and business owners who don’t feel the mandate is appropriate.

Watch the video and if you’re going to take action on ANY of it, be sure to consult with a professional to help you.

This is to merely help you start the conversation.

NOTE: This is not a discussion on whether the 💉 is effective or not, it’s a post about the rights of business owners’ and their employees!

node.text:
Do you like getting tax-free money out of your business? Who doesn’t!

If you’re a business owner and use your home to work from, you have a couple options you may be able to take advantage of.

The two most common are: the “Augusta Rule” and the Home Office Deduction.

But which is better for you?

Before I get into that, for those who aren’t aware: There’s a rule known as the “Augusta Rule” that says, if you rent your PRINCIPAL RESIDENCE out for under 15 days per year, then that income is considered non-taxable.
 To use this in your business, once per month you can hold a meeting with all of your shareholders (that might be just you) and cut a check from your business account to your personal account. This is deductible to the business as rent expenses and TAX-FREE rental income to you.

The other option is the home office deduction, which says that if you use an area of your home EXCLUSIVELY FOR BUSINESS, you can deduct that percentage of the costs of your home.

So which is better for you? If you own your home, in almost every case the Augusta Rule is going to be a better deduction.

This is partly because it’s a business expense and partly because you already get the mortgage interest and property taxes on your itemized deductions.

If you rent your home, then you can’t use the Augusta Rule, so by definition the home office is better for you.

Are you taking advantage of either? Let me know in the comments!

Down here in Bal Harbour area of Miami for a couple days celebrating my birthday and getting some excellent recharge time.

The last couple days have me thinking:

When Tony Robbins says “people overestimate what they can do in a year and underestimate what they can do in a decade,” he is absolutely correct.

Yesterday I officially entered the second half of my 30s and turned 36.

When I look at my life at age 30 compared to today, just 6 years later, I am in awe of how much has evolved in that time.

On my 30th birthday, I didn’t even have my CPA license yet.

Now I am blessed to speak on national stages, and in my private coaching group, teaching about what I do.

My family is growing into a tight-knit crew and we love making memories together.

This summer we moved across the country and live 10 minutes from the beach—something I’ve always dreamed of.

The power of creating a vision, and consistently working towards it day in and day out, can NOT be understated.

The other thing that happens when you pursue your vision is you find out your UNIQUE ABILITY.

This last year I’ve got really honed in and  learned that I’m uniquely equipped to teach a confusing topic (taxes and business numbers) in a way that people seem to understand a little easier.

You can’t find your UNIQUE ABILITY without putting in the work.

That’s a fact. You have to bump your head against 40 different walls to see what works and what doesn’t.

But the main lesson here is this: just start.

If you’ve got a dream, get started in little ways towards it.

Every day, put 5-15 minutes towards improving.

Do that, consistently over 5 or 10 years, and you will be amazed at what happens in your life.

And one day, you’ll be celebrating your birthday looking back at the first social media post you made or the first prospect call you dialed, and be in awe of how far you’ve come.

Go DO.

Do you ever feel like you’re spinning your wheels in your business but not actually making any money?

You might be focusing on the wrong things, especially when it comes to expenses!

Too often I see business owners focus on little things because they feel in control, rather than big things that will really move the needle.

An example of this is focusing on office supplies.

Do you see an employee buying extra reams of paper or coffee K-cups and get mad because it’s “waste”?

I’ve never seen a business thrive or die because they bought too many K-cups.

They have gone under, though, because they hired too fast or spent too much on materials.

You should have a budget for all expenses in your business, but make sure you’re spending the MAJORITY of your time on the ones that truly will move the needle for you—not the ones that you give you a sense of control.

How much cash do you typically keep in your business?

Do you live in continuous anxiety because your cash accounts are running too low?

Ideally, you should target having a cash balance of at least 3-6 months of expenses in your bank account, depending on your business.

By having cash reserves you will not only sleep better at night, you will make better DECISIONS in your business.

Because when cash runs low you can get desperate, and desperation usually leads to taking on clients or revenue streams you shouldn’t.

The other thing having cash reserves protects you from, as we’ve seen this year, is going out of business in the case of a forced shut down.
